# Musician beat — the OODA cadence hook.
#
# Fired by the kernel beat scheduler on this context's coarse cadence
# (default: every 8 phrases of 16 beats @ 120 BPM). `kj drive` publishes a
# turn request for the current context; the server's turn driver runs the
# model turn. Its ABC output is committed to the shared score on the beat,
# and MIDI is derived from that committed notation for playback — notation
# is the score, MIDI a render. This script is the user-editable seam — change
# the prompt, gate the drive on conditions, or add pre-beat bookkeeping here.
#
# The beat scheduler seeds this run with the transport report (KJ_-prefixed,
# matching the kernel-injection convention — cf. KJ_PARENT_BLOCK_COUNT):
#   $KJ_TICK      — the track's playhead tick (beat index, frozen off-beat)
#   $KJ_PHRASE    — phrases elapsed while playing
#   $KJ_TEMPO     — tempo in whole BPM
#   $KJ_HEARD     — JSON array of recent committed notation across tracks
#                   ([{tick, track, abc}, …], oldest→newest). The score blocks
#                   are hydration-silent, so this is the only way the player
#                   sees what was just played. (Stopgap JSON string; becomes a
#                   kaish array + a read-on-demand pull once arrays land.)
#   $KJ_PULSE     — per-attachment monotonic wakeup counter; reliable ordering
#                   key (unlike KJ_TICK, which can freeze off-beat)
#   $KJ_EPOCH_NS  — wall-clock ns, shared across all contexts woken the same beat
# Composed into the --prompt below, they become the turn's transport report:
# the fresh suffix the player reads each beat.
#
# `kj drive --prompt` writes the report as a real User block, so the model
# hydrates it as the fresh user turn (not a discarded seed).
#
# No positional context: the tick lifecycle runs with this context as the
# current one, so `kj drive` targets it (avoids passing the raw id as an arg).
kj drive --prompt "Transport: tick $KJ_TICK, phrase $KJ_PHRASE, $KJ_TEMPO BPM. Recently played (JSON): $KJ_HEARD. Play the next phrase and give it as one complete, self-contained ABC tune every turn — a full header (X:, T:, M:, L:, K:) then the body, never a bare phrase or a continuation: the score parser rejects a body without a header. Raw ABC only — no prose, no code fences."
